			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Dog nuzzled me awake, as he was wont to do every morning, his cold, damp nose touching my neck below my ear.  With a small start, I was wide-awake.  “Dog!” I grumbled as I rubbed my neck.  “You’d think after all this time I’d be used to that cold nose of yours!”  Dog sat in front of me, a wide grin on his face, tongue lolling to one side.  With a toss of his head he woofed, bounced up and pounced on a stick near the cooling fire.  Grabbing it in his powerful jaws that could have splintered it with little effort he picked it up and tossed it into the sir, leaping playfully to catch it before it dropped and then gamboled over to where I still sat on my furs to lay it at my feet.  I reached out with both hands and grabbed handfuls of fur and ear, giving them a good scratching.  I ran my hands down the massive neck to the powerful shoulders and on to check his back, hips and legs.  His fur was a thick, springy snow white and as usual he was in fine form.  After a little more petting I picked up the stick he had so playfully brought me to stir my fire back up and set a pot of water on the fire to heat for a hot cup of tea.  I was starting to check my bags to see what was for breakfast when I looked up to see Dog trotting back into camp with a snow bunny dangling from between his jaws.  “Rabbit again, huh?” I said to him as I reached for it to begin preparing it.  While Dog did eat his meals raw, he also enjoyed cooked rabbit and he brought me one whenever he could and would eagerly wait as I prepared it and cooked it over the glowing coals.  I pulled off a portion for myself and offered the remaining portion of the carcass to him.  Dog gingerly pulled the steaming meat off of the stick and laid it between his paws in the snow.  I fixed myself a hot cup of tea and then poured some hot water into his water dish as well, dropping in a handful of snow to cool it slightly.  Once we finished eating I broke camp. 
<br />

<br />
 Dog and I strolled up the sloping ravine to the windswept plateau above our campsite.  I stood there looking out across the snowy Tundra of my homeland, one arm draped comfortably across Dog’s back, running my thinly gloved fingers thru the thick fur on his shoulder.  “I never tire of looking across the Tundra, Dog,” I said.  Wandering across the broken land in front of me were small herds of mammoths, young calves following their mothers, the matriarchs and bulls sporting the long curved tusks that hunters valued along with their hides and meat.  Giant wooly spiders crawled over the ravines; they also were hunted for their silks that were used in tailoring many useful items.  Snow leopards briefly appeared as they hunted their prey.  I smiled when I saw one dash from one hidden area to another, remembering one of my sleeping furs was a black-spotted, snowy white hide from one of my first Tundra kills.  A low growl from Dog brought my attention to a small band of wandering Orcs in a nearby ravine, obviously waiting, hoping to waylay some hapless hunter.  Again a growl rumbled from Dog’s throat.  With a pat to his shoulder I cast my fist towards the Orcs, “Kill ‘em, Dog!”  Dog bounded down the ravine to drop among the Orcs and savagely attacked them.  Pouncing on one after another, tearing and mauling them in short order.  Soon the ground and his fur were stained violet from their blood.  Dog shook himself from head to tail, splattering the surrounding area with droplets of blood and offal that had clung to his fur.  “Get yourself cleaned up, Dog… Good work!”  Dog woofed back, obviously satisfied with the morning slaughter.  Neither he nor I had any love for Orcs as they had been our childhood foes, and Dog took quite a grisly pleasure in ridding Norrath of any we found.  Dog plunged into a pristine snowdrift a short distance away from the carnage, cleaning the remaining blood from his fur.  It was never smart to wander around any area smelling of blood, Dog knew this as well and he rubbed himself in the snow to clean his fur, and then shook himself mightily to remove the last vestiges of violet. 
<br />

<br />
Dog bounded back to me and butted his broad head against my chest for a moment as I dug my fingers into his thick fur.  I raised his head and looked into his intelligent eyes, “OK, Dog, no more playing.  We’re not heading back to the Wayfarer’s camp today, we’re heading home.”  Dog cocked his head and looked at me with a quizzical expression on his face “Yes, home, we’re off to Halas today, Dog.  I need to talk to the Guildmaster.”  Dog woofed and tossed his head, pulling away from my grasp, and took a few steps toward Halas then stopped and pointedly looked at me, I could almost hear him saying “So why aren’t you moving?”  I laughed, “I’m coming!” We made our way across the Tundra towards the mountains in the distance.  As we approached the snowy passageway, I waved at the guards as I past into the ravines that led toward Halas.  I stopped occasionally to buff or heal the young ones playing and hunting in the area near Halas and the Book to the Plane of Knowledge, and then turned into the cut that led to Halas.  Shunning the slow boat that shuttled back and forth, Dog and I plunged into the icy water that protected the entrance to Halas, quickly traversing the short distance to the dock on the other side.  After shaking off the majority of the icy water Dog and I wandered into the city, stopping at a favorite Pub and chatting a bit with some old friends I hadn’t seen in the few years it had been since my last return to my hometown.  After a bit we left the Pub and headed to the Guildmaster’s lodge near the wolf enclosure, Dog walking stately at my side.  Ranged in front of the lodge, sitting in the snow, were the young, hopeful beastlord candidates, eagerly listening to the Old Guildmaster as he told them tales of great deeds and instructed them on the lore of the Beastlord.  I chuckled to myself as the young ones noticed Dog’s and my approach, it was almost a wave of excitement starting with a few and spreading to encompass all of them, their eyes widening as they took in the size of Dog in comparison to the pups that they tended that had come looking for a life-companion.  Beastlords did not choose the wolf they wanted, rather it was the wolf that chose the beastlord, I thought back to my own bonding with Dog and smiled.  “Julz!” the Guildmaster called out as he noticed our approach.  I grinned in response and waved as Dog and I walked past the young men and women who had hastily scrambled to their feet at our approach.  The Guildmaster and I clasped forearms in greeting before exchanging a backslapping hug.  With a wave he dismissed his young charges and drew me into his lodge to talk.  Dog followed and lay near the fire.  I glimpsed a few of the young hopefuls head toward the wolf enclosure to speak to the young wolves as I entered the lodge, and I grinned at the memory of when I had seen my first adult warder.  “That’ll give them something to dream about tonight!” the Guildmaster chuckled.  Over pints of brew and a hot pot of stew he and I discussed the happenings in Norrath and what I had learned about the new lands that Morden Rasp had discovered.  We talked long into the night and before Dog and I departed in the wee hours of the morning the old Guildmaster has extracted a promise from me to return again.  I smiled at the man I now knew as friend, “I will, my friend. “ I said as we clasped forearms and exchanged a hug.  “How else can you train our youngsters if you don’t know what is happening in Norrath, though I know you have others that bring you information as well.” I laughed, “But I will return, the Tundra draws me back every time!”  The Guildmaster grinned back at me, ”It’s in the blood, Girl, it’s in the blood…” I nodded, my eyes already searching the distance.  Cities never held Dog and me long, and already I was yearning for the wide-open expanses to roam.  The Guildmaster saw my eyes searching the distance and a sadness touched his face.  “Go on Girl, I know it calls you, time enough when you get old to have to settle for a city to live in… Go!”  Understanding flashed between us and I clasped his shoulder once more then signaled to Dog as I headed out the door.  I knew he was standing there watching me leave; yet I did not look back.  As Dog and I strode thru the barely awake city a young man stepped out from the shadows alongside one of the nearby lodges.  Dog stopped and looked at the young man standing proudly in the snow  “I’m going to be a Beastlord!” he said in a confidant voice.  Dog woofed once.  I looked at Dog and smiled.  Glancing at the young man I said, “You will.”  I nodded at him as Dog and I continued our way out of the city.  Behind us the young man looked off into the distant mountains, the lonely howl of a young wolf holding his attention.  The Legacy continues…
<br />

